1 d. The superintendent of the state highway patrol, or the superintendent's designee;
2 and
3 e. A representative from each of the federally recognized Indian nations, tribes, or
4 bands in this state, appointed by the attorney general from a list of two or more
5 nominees from the chairman of each tribe.
6 4. While respecting the government-to-government relationship between the state and
7 each tribe, the primary duties of the task force are to:
8 a. Identify jurisdictional barriers between federal, state, local, and tribal law
9 enforcement and community agencies;
10 b. Identify causes that contribute to missing and murdered indigenous people and
11 make recommendations to federally recognized tribes in the state to reduce
12 cases of missing and murdered indigenous people;
13 c. Identify strategies to improve interagency communication, cooperation, and
14 collaboration to remove jurisdictional barriers and increase reporting and
15 investigation of missing indigenous people; and
16 d. Administer the missing indigenous people grant fund.
17 5. The task force shall submit a report of its activities, findings, and any
18 recommendations to the legislative management by August first of each year. The
19 report must include:
20 a. The number of indigenous individuals reported missing in the missing person
21 repository;
22 b. The number of indigenous individuals recovered as a result of the missing person
23 repository;
24 c. The number of indigenous individuals recovered as a result of the missing
25 indigenous people grant fund;
26 d. The number of missing indigenous individuals searched for and recovered;
27 e. The number of missing indigenous individuals entries into the missing person
28 repository by year;
29 f. An analysis by year of the characteristics of missing indigenous people, including
30 age, gender, child protective services involvement status, foster case status,
31 duration of time missing, and estimated related cause;
